Monte Carlo Error

Zihan Fang

09/06/2020

1 Introduction

In this blog, I will first demonstrate the concepts of absolute error and relative error when estimating probabilities from simulation. Then, I will explain why the concept is important, introduce key vocabulary terms, and demonstrate the concept in action.

I will perform a 14 X 5 factorial experiment simulation that estimates the error for each combination of replicate number (2^2, 2^3, …, 2^15) and probability (0.01, 0.05, 0.10, 0.25, 0.50). p̂ denote the probability estimated from simulation, and p denote the true underlying probability.

Calculate error as:

absolute error=|p̂−p|
relative error=|p̂−p|/p

1.1 Background

Simulation error The simulation produces an approximate answer; there is some degree of error in the number estimated by the Monte Carlo simulation. Intuitively, as the number of simulation repetitions increases, the degree of error should decrease.

1.1.1 Absolute Error

The difference between the measured or inferred value of a quantity and its actual value is called the absolute error. The absolute error of the sum or difference of a number of quantities is less than or equal to the sum of their absolute errors. (source:https://mathworld.wolfram.com/AbsoluteError.html#)

1.1.2 Relative Error

Relative error is a measure of the uncertainty of measurement compared to the size of the measurement. It’s used to put error into perspective. (source:https://www.thoughtco.com/definition-of-relative-error-605609)

2 Methods

In this simulation, Sample Size is (2^2, 2^3, …, 2^15), R is the number of replicates, true underlying probability is P=(0.01, 0.05, 0.10, 0.25, 0.50). I saved them as a parameters list. Then, I defined a function to estimate probabilities. Here Absolute error(ae) = |p_hat - p|, Relative error(re) |p_hat - p|/p where p_hat= parameters$p_hat, p = parameters$p. To show how the error evolve, we have to repeat the simulation, and I use a “for” loop to achieve that.

require(magrittr)
# Simulation Parameters
#   Number of Replicates
R <- 5000 
# Parameters
#   Sample Size = 2^(2:15)
#   Underlying true probability = c(0.01, 0.05, 0.1, 0.25, 0.5)
#   parameters a list
parameters <- list(R = 5000, ss = 4, p = 0.1)

# Process
#   Generating binomial RV of a specific sample size and specific probability 
create_data_estimate_p <- function(parameters){
  parameters$p_hat <- rbinom(parameters$R, parameters$ss,  parameters$p)/parameters$ss
  parameters
}

#   Absolute error(ae) |p_hat - p|
absolute_error <- function(parameters){
  abs(parameters$p_hat - parameters$p)
}

#   Relative error(re) |p_hat - p|/p
relative_error <- function(parameters){
  abs(parameters$p_hat - parameters$p)/parameters$p
}

# Repeat
#   Distributions
one_p_n <- function(parameters){
 ae <- parameters %>% create_data_estimate_p %>% absolute_error
 re <- ae/parameters$p
 mae <- mean(ae)
 mre <- mean(re) 
 c(mae,mre)
}

simulation_settings <- expand.grid(
  R = 5000
, p = c(0.01, 0.05, 0.1, 0.25, 0.5)
, ss = 2^(2:15)
, mae = NA_real_
, mre = NA_real_
, KEEP.OUT.ATTRS = FALSE
)

for(i in 1:nrow(simulation_settings)){
  simulation_settings[i, c("mae","mre")] <- simulation_settings[i, ] %>% as.list %>% one_p_n()
}

2.1 Plots-log2

2.1.1 MAE

# Define functions
require(dtplyr)
require(showtext)
require(sysfonts)
require(showtextdb)
require(tidyverse)
plotstyle <- function(data = NULL, style = NULL,...){
  pstl <- deparse(substitute(style))
  
  if(pstl == "NULL"){
    par(
      mar=c(1,1,.1,.1)*2,
      mgp=c(1,0,0),
      tcl=.2,
      cex.axis=.75,
      col.axis="black",
      pch=16
    )
  }else if(pstl == "tight"){
    par(
      mar=c(1,1,.01,.01)*2,
      mgp=c(1,0,0),
      tcl=.2,
      cex.axis=.75,
      col.axis="black"
    )
  }else if(pstl == "upright"){
    par(
      mar=c(1.1,1.1,.1,.1)*2,
      mgp=c(1.1,0.1,0),
      tcl=.2,
      cex.axis=.75,
      col.axis="black",
      pch = 16,
      las = 1
    )
  }
  par(...)
  invisible(data)
}

plot_setup <- function(d, f, xlim = NULL, ylim = NULL, log = "", asp = NA, xaxs = "r", yaxs = "r", ...){
  #browser()
  if(is.null(f)){
    v <- 1:4; dim(v) <- c(2,2)
  }else{
    v <- model.frame(f, data = d) %>% apply(2, range)  
  }
  
  if(is.null(xlim)) xlim <- v[,2]
  if(is.null(ylim)) ylim <- v[,1]
  plot.new()
  par(...)
  plot.window(xlim = xlim, ylim = ylim, log = log, asp = asp, xaxs = xaxs, yaxs = yaxs)
  d
}
lwith <- function(l, ...) lapply(l, function(x, ...){with(x, ...)}, ... )
`%|%` <- function(a,b) paste0(a,b)

# plot-MAE
simulation_settings %>%
  mutate(col = factor(p) %>% as.numeric) %>%
  plotstyle(upright,mar=c(3,3,2,1)) %>%
  plot_setup(mae ~ log(ss,base=2)) %>%
  split(.$p) %>%
  lwith({
    lines(log(ss,base=2),mae, type = "b", col = col[1], lwd =4)
    c(p[1],col[1])
  }) %>%
  do.call("rbind", . ) %>%
  (function(x){
    legend("topright", legend = "p=" %|% x[,1],col = x[,2], lwd = 4, bty="n")
  })
box()
axis(side = 1, at = axTicks(1), labels = 2^axTicks(1))
axis(2)
title(main = "Mean Absolute Error")
title(ylab = "MAE",line = 2)
title(xlab = "Sample Size(log2 Scale)", line = 1.5)


In this picture, MAE means the average difference between true probability and experiment probability, and the x-axis is the sample size and shows log2 sets. From the output, we can see when underlying true probability become greater, the mean abosolute error will be larger. But if the sample size is big enough the mean absolute error become small and is going to zero. With the sample size increasing, the mean absolute error decrease and the difference between different true probabilities become smaller. So, if we want to find the true probability we need large sample size and replicate more times.

2.1.2 MRE

#plot-MRE
simulation_settings %>%
  mutate(col = factor(p) %>% as.numeric) %>%
  plotstyle(upright,mar=c(3,3,2,1)) %>%
  plot_setup(mre ~ log(ss,base=2)) %>%
  split(.$p) %>%
  lwith({
    lines(log(ss,base=2), mre, type = "b", col = col[1], lwd =4)
    c(p[1],col[1])
  }) %>%
  do.call("rbind", . ) %>%
  (function(x){
    legend("topright", legend = "p=" %|% x[,1], col = x[,2], lwd = 4, bty="n")
  })
box()
axis(side = 1, at = axTicks(1), labels = 2^axTicks(1))
axis(2)
title(main = "Mean Relative Error")
title(ylab = "MRE", line = 2)
title(xlab = "Sample Size(log2 Scale)", line = 1.5)


In this picture, MRE means the average relative error, and the x-axis is also the sample size and shows log2 set. From the output, we can see when underlying true probability become greater, the mean relative error will be smaller. But if the sample size is big enough the mean relative error become small and is going to zero. On the whole, the mean relative error is larger than mean absolute error.

From the output, we can see when underlying true probability become greater, the mean absolute error will be larger. But if the sample size is big enough the mean absolute error become small and is going to zero. On the whole, the mean absolute error is small and equal to the mean absolute error of log2 set. With the sample size increasing, the mean absolute error decrease and the difference between different true probabilities become smaller. So, if we want to find the true probability we need large sample size and replicate more times.
